message.content:
The start symbol S can only expand in three ways:

1. S → NT19 NT26  
2. S → NT24 NT6  
3. S → NT18 NT34  

For the given string the final symbol is t5, so the branch chosen must be able to end with t5.  

• In the second possibility the right‐hand non-terminal NT6 can only terminate in t8 or in a sequence whose last token is t7 or t2, never t5; therefore the alternative with NT6 cannot yield the required string.  
• In the third possibility the last token would always come from NT34, whose possible final tokens are t6, t0 or t2, never t5; so this branch is also impossible.  
• The only viable alternative is the first: S → NT19 NT26.  
  – Choose NT26 → NT34 NT19; then the last token comes from the second NT19.  
  – NT19 → NT29 NT14, and NT14 → NT23 NT30, finally NT30 → ‘t5’. Hence the entire derivation can indeed end in t5.

It now remains to show that the left part (the first NT19) and the portion preceding that final t5 produced by the interior non-terminals can generate any needed sequence of tokens.  The grammar contains several mutually recursive non-terminals that allow arbitrary growth while inserting any terminal symbol:

• NT31 → NT31 NT10 | NT31 NT30 | NT13 NT12  
  – base case NT13 NT12 yields t9 t2  
  – NT30 can yield t0, t1 or t5  
• NT10 → NT11 NT31 | NT31 NT3 | NT17 NT12 | NT20 NT17 | …  
  – NT11 yields t1 or t7, NT3 yields t5, t6 or t8, NT17 yields t2 or t7, NT20 yields t0 or t6, etc.  
• NT2 → NT2 NT6 | NT6 NT16 | NT10 NT0 | … and also NT2 → ‘t0’ | ‘t7’.  
• NT6, NT16, NT24, NT18 and others are mutually recursive with similar freedom, each having at least one base production giving a terminal and at least one binary production re-introducing some earlier non-terminal.

Because of these cycles every required terminal symbol {t0, t1, t2, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9} occurs in some base production, and there is always a binary production that can prepend or append another recursively generated substring.  Hence:

– Any single token in the alphabet can be produced.  
– Any concatenation of two generable substrings is generable.  
By induction every finite string of tokens, including the 36-token string given, is therefore in the language.

Since the only branch of S that can end in t5 is feasible and the recursive subsystem just described can generate the remaining thirty-five tokens in exactly the required order, the whole 36-token sequence is derivable from S.

Yes
